s and grandmothers, provide a vivid picture of lives caught in the intersection of race, class, and gender.Kaplan challenges the assumption conveyed in the popular media that the African-American community condones teen pregnancy, single parenting, and reliance on welfare. Especially telling are the feelings of frustration, anger, and disappointment expressed by the mothers and grandmothers Kaplan interviewed. And in listening to teenage mothers discuss their problems, Kaplan hears first-hand of their misunderstandings regarding sex, their fraught relationships with men, and their difficulties with the educational system—all factors that bear heavily on their status as young parents.Kaplan's own experience as an African-American teenage mother adds a personal dimension to this book, and she offers substantial proposals for rethinking and reassessing the class factors, gender relations, and racism that influence black teenagers to become mothers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAfrican American teenage mothersvCase studies. 0aTeenage pregnancyzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aTeenage pregnancyzUnited StateszUnited StatesxCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh  aafrican american studies.  aafrican american.  ablack community.  ablack culture.  ablack teen mom.  ablack teenagers.  ablack teens.  ablack women.  ablack.  aclass.  aeducation.  aethnic studies.  afamily relationships.  afeminism.  agender.  ajustice.  amedia.  anonfiction.  apoverty.  apregnancy.  aprejudice.  arace.  aracism.  asex education.  asex.  asingle parent.  asocial issues.  asociology.  astereotypes.  ateen girls.  ateen mom.  ateen pregnancy.  ateenage mother.  ateenage motherhood.  awelfare system.  awelfare.  awomen studies.  a